body:
For #81521

Extracts `FileCommands.doSave` to a new save service. This service currently just delegates to the `textFileService`. However the goal is that we could expand the `SaveService` to support saving non-text resources, such as a webviews panels that are not tied to a resource on disk. One example use case of this type of webview would be editing a document stored online. For that case, we likely still want to support save but do not want save to go through `ITextFileService`

@bpasero I'd appreciate your feedback on if you feel that introducing a `SaveService` is the right approach here and what we think should live in it

- VSCode Version: 1.38.1 (as well as 1.39.0-insider)
- OS Version: Mac 10.14.6

When calling `fetchTasks({ type: '<my-custom-type>' })`, any matching tasks returned have been "resolved" into the their underlying ShellExecute/ProcessExecute/CustomExecution types and the `definition` property will not include any properties set by the user in `tasks.json`.  This prevents extensions from (easily) selecting one of those tasks based on a given property of that definition.

For example, in our case we have a property of our custom task that refers to a specific file within the workspace. If we want to execute that task when a command is invoked on the associated file's context menu, we'd like to be able to something along the lines of:

```typescript
const filename = ...;
const tasks = vscode.tasks.fetchTasks({ type: '<my-custom-type'});
const matchingFileTasks = tasks.filter(task => task.definition.filename === filename);

let selectedFileTask;
if (matchingFileTasks.length === 1) {
  selectedFileTask = matchingFileTasks[0];
} else if (matchingFileTasks.length > 1) {
  selectedFileTask = quickPickTask(matchingFileTasks);
} else {
  throw new Error('No tasks found.');
}

vscode.tasks.executeTask(selectedFileTask);
```

A `DebugConfigurationProvider` may resolve a configuration that includes a `preLaunchTask`.  This task will be executed after resolution (obviously) but executed before the debugging session starts.

There are several scenarios (e.g. in the case of Docker debugging) where details of the debugging session (e.g. the port to which the debugger should attach) may ultimately depend on that pre-launch task (e.g. mapping a given container port to a host port).  However, because the debug configuration is resolved *before* the task executes, it requires upfront agreement between the task configuration and the debug configuration and precludes the debug configuration being derived from the *result* of the pre-launch task.  E.g. the user must explicitly choose a port for both to use rather than the pre-launch task determine an available port and have debug configuration use that available port.

It would be helpful if a `DebugConfigurationProvider` had a means of deferring resolution of certain properties of its configuration until *after* the pre-launch task (if any) has executed.  The `DebugConfigurationProvider` could then use the results of that execution to alter its previously resolved configuration (if necessary).

An, initial, likely naive API might look like:

```typescript
interface DebugConfigurationProvider {
    // Existing API:
    provideDebugConfigurations(folder: WorkspaceFolder | undefined, token?: CancellationToken): ProviderResult<DebugConfiguration[]>;
    resolveDebugConfiguration(folder: WorkspaceFolder | undefined, debugConfiguration: DebugConfiguration, token?: CancellationToken): ProviderResult<DebugConfiguration | undefined>;

    // Proposed API:
    // Called after the preLaunchTask successfully executes but before debugging starts and includes the executed pre-launch task object (presumably used to derive any necessary changes).
    resolveDebugConfigurationPostLaunchTask?(folder: WorkspaceFolder | undefined, debugConfiguration: DebugConfiguration, preLaunchTask: Task, token?: CancellationToken): ProviderResult<DebugConfiguration | undefined>
}
```
